<dl id="n38145a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38145a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38145a"> 145(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> (peat, pit, / part, port / put, &amp;c</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">It stands to reason that if we are to identify each of the 13 words: <mark>peat, pit, pate, pet, pat, pe(r)t, putt, pa(r)t, pot, port, pote, poot, put</mark>, without uncertainly <font color="green">[sic]</font>, we must form the various vowel postures, which distinguish them, with accuracy. <small> Sir Richard Paget, <a name="RPBP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RPBP"><cite title="source">Babel, or The Past, Present and Future of Human Speech</cite></a> (1930) 76</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
